05476nam a22006975i 9780824837860DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20132013hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248378607 a10.1515/97808248378602doi  a(DE-B1597)484663  a(OCoLC)859157560  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBL2240.C53bK35 2013 7aREL0240002bisacsh04a299/.572231 aKallander, George L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSalvation through Dissent :bTonghak Heterodoxy and Early Modern Korea /cGeorge L. Kallander; ed. by Robert E. Buswell. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKorean Classics Library: Philosophy and Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Securing the People: Orthodoxy, Heterodoxy, and the Confucian State -- t2. Uncertain Times, Uncertain Means: Rural Life, Western Ways, and Ch’oe Cheu -- t3. Kumi Mountain: Center of the World, 1861–1863 -- t4. The Tonghaks Have Again Arisen, 1864–1894 -- t5. Another Tonghak Revolution, 1904–1907 -- tConclusion -- tTranslations -- tEastern Scripture -- tSelections from Songs of Yongdam -- tSelections from Master Haewŏl’s Discussion on the Teachings -- tCh’oe Sihyŏng’s Petitions -- tAccount of the Origin of the Way -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Names, Terms, and Phrases -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA popular teaching that combined elements of Confucianism, Daoism, Buddhism, folk beliefs, and Catholicism, Tonghak (Eastern Learning) is best known for its involvement in a rebellion that touched off the Sino-Japanese War (1894–1895) and accelerated Japanese involvement in Korea. Through a careful reading of sources—including religious works and biographies many of which are translated and annotated here into English for the first time—Salvation through Dissent traces Tonghak’s rise amidst the debates over orthodoxy and heterodoxy in Chosŏn Korea (1392–1910) and its impact on religious and political identity from 1860 to 1906. It argues that the teachings of founder Ch’oe Cheu (1824–1864) attracted a large following among rural Koreans by offering them spiritual and material promises to relieve conditions such as poverty and disease and provided consolation in a tense geo-political climate. Following Ch’oe Cheu’s martyrdom, his successors reshaped Tonghak doctrine and practice not only to ensure the survival of the religious community, but also address shifting socio-political needs. Their call for religious and social reforms led to an uprising in 1894 and subsequent military intervention by China and Japan.The work locates the origins of Korea’s twentieth-century religious nationalist movement in the aftermath of the 1894 rebellion, the resurgence of Japanese power after the Russo-Japanese War (1904–1905), and the re-creation of Tonghak as Ch’ŏngogyo (the Religion of the Heavenly Way) in 1905. As a study of religion and politics, Salvation through Dissent adds a new layer of understanding to Korea’s changing interactions with the world and the world’s involvement with Korea. In addition to students and scholars of Korea’s early modern period, it will appeal to those interested in global politics, Chinese and Japanese studies, world religion, international relations, and peasant history. The extensive, annotated translations will be of particular use in courses on Korea, East Asia, and global religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aReligion and statezKoreaxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh1 aBuswell, Robert E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483786040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824837860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824837860.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK